{{Infobox power station | name = Arecleoch Wind Farm | name_official = | image = Geograph-3419211-Arecleoch-Wind-Farm.jpg | image_size = 250px | image_caption = Arecleoch Wind Farm | image_alt = Several wind turbines with a gravel path leading around them. | location_map = UK Scotland | relief=1 | location_map_size = | location_map_caption = Location of Arecleoch Wind Farm in Scotland | coordinates = {{coord|55|03|12|N|04|52|56|W|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline,title}} | coordinates_ref = | country = Scotland, United Kingdom | location = [[South Ayrshire]] | status = O | construction_began = 2009 | commissioned = June 2011 | decommissioned = | cost = | owner = [[ScottishPower Renewables]] | operator = [[Scottish Power]] | ps_units_operational = 60 X 2&nbsp;MW | ps_units_manu_model = [[Gamesa Corporación Tecnológica|Gamesa]]: G80 | wind_hub_height = | wind_rotor_diameter = | wind_rated_speed = | wind_farm_type = Onshore | wind_site_elevation = | wind_site_usage = | wind_site_area = | ps_electrical_capacity = 120 [[Megawatt|MW]] | ps_electrical_cap_fac = | website = | extra = }} '''Arecleoch Wind Farm''' is a 60 turbine [[wind farm]] in [[South Ayrshire]], [[Scotland]] with a total capacity of 120 [[megawatts]] (MW), enough to power over 67,000 homes.<ref name="Renewable UK">[http://bwea.com/ukwed/operational.asp UK Operational Wind Farms – Renewable UK] Accessed 27 September 2011</ref> Construction started in 2009 and it was commissioned in June 2011.<ref name="Renewable UK" /><ref>[http://www.renewables-map.co.uk/details.asp?pageid=15 Arecleoch Wind Farm – Renewables Map] Accessed 27 September 2011</ref>
== Incidents == In January and February 2016 there were two separate incidents of a turbine catching fire overnight while the site was unmanned due to faults in the mechanism housing. The turbines were destroyed and were disassembled and removed from site. Scottish Power reported to the Sunday Mail on 10 April 2016 they were investigating these incidents along with the manufacturer Gamesa. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pressreader.com/uk/sunday-mail-uk/20160410/282183650208296|title=PressReader.com - Connecting People Through News|website=www.pressreader.com|access-date=2016-04-18}}</ref>
In December 2016 a third turbine caught fire during high winds while it was switched off for maintenance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pressreader.com/uk/scottish-daily-mail/20161227/281792808688409|title=PressReader.com - Connecting People Through News|website=www.pressreader.com|access-date=2016-12-27}}</ref> The turbine was left to burn itself out and was destroyed.
In October 2017 a fourth turbine caught fire and was also left to burn itself out and was destroyed.
