{{lead too short|date=February 2017}}
{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2013}}
'''Cotton paper''', also known as '''rag paper''', is made using [[cotton linter]]s or [[cotton]] from used [[cloth]] (rags) as the primary material. Important documents are often printed on cotton paper, because it is known to last many years without deterioration. Cotton paper is superior in both strength and durability to [[wood-pulp paper|wood pulp-based paper]], which may contain high concentrations of [[acids]], and also absorbs [[ink]] or [[toner]] better. Different grades of cotton paper can be produced.

==Properties==
High-quality cotton fibre paper is known to last hundreds of years without appreciable fading, discoloration, or deterioration,<ref>{{cite web|last= |first= |authorlink= |title=What is 100% Cotton Bond Paper? |work= |publisher=George Mason University |url=http://www.gmu.edu/library/specialcollections/dtcottonpaper.html |doi= |accessdate=February 7, 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201015106/http://www.gmu.edu/library/specialcollections/dtcottonpaper.html |archivedate=December 1, 2008 }}</ref> so it is often used for important documents, such as the archival copies of dissertations or theses. As a rule of thumb, for each percentage point of cotton fibre, a user may expect one year of resisting deterioration by use (the handling to which paper may be subjected).<ref>Southworth Paper Co {{better reference|date=September 2013}}</ref> Legal document paper typically contains 25% cotton. Cotton paper will produce a better printout than [[copy paper]] because it can more readily absorb [[ink]] or [[toner]].{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}

Cotton paper is typically graded as 25%, 50%, or 100% cotton.  Usually it can be checked by holding the cotton paper up to the light and looking just below the [[watermark]] for a number.  100% cotton paper may contain small amounts of acids, and should be tested or certified before use for archival documents.

Second-cut cotton linters have a normal average fibre length of 1.45&nbsp;µm, and have similar properties as a short [[softwood]] [[pulp (paper)|pulp]].<ref>{{Cite book| last = Nanko | first = Hirko |author2=Button, Allan |author3=Hillman, Dave | title = The World of Market Pulp | publisher = WOMP, LLC | year = 2005 | location = Appleton, WI, USA | page = 62| url =  | doi =  | id =  | isbn = 0-615-13013-5 }}</ref>

==Uses==
Cotton bond paper can be found at most stores that sell stationery and other office products.  Some cotton paper contains a [[watermark]]. It is used for [[banknotes]] in a number of countries. These banknotes are typically made from 100% cotton paper, but can also be made with a mixture of 75% or less [[flax]].<ref>{{cite web|last= |first= |authorlink= |title=Banknotes design and production |work= |publisher=Bank of Canada |url=http://www.bankofcanada.ca/en/banknotes/facts.html |doi= |accessdate=February 7, 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216040303/http://www.bankofcanada.ca/en/banknotes/facts.html |archivedate=December 16, 2008 }}</ref> Other materials may also be used and still be known as ''[[currency paper]]''.

Higher quality art papers are often made from cotton.

It has found extensive use as a [[printed circuit board]] substrate when mixed with epoxy resins and classified into CEM 1, CEM 2 etc.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}

==History==
{{See also|History of paper|Pulp (paper)|Deinking}}
Cotton was first used with a mixture of [[silk]] to make paper called Carta Bombycina. In the 1800s, [[fiber crop]]s such as [[flax]] fibres or cotton from used [[cloth]]s (rags) were the primary material source. By the turn of the 20th century, most paper was made from wood pulp, but cotton is still used in specialty papers. As cotton rags now often contain [[Synthetic fibers|synthetic fibres]], papermakers have turned to second-cut cotton linters as raw material sources for making pulp for cotton papers.<ref name=wmp>{{Cite book| last1=Nanko |first1=Hirko |last2=Button |first2=Allan |last3=Hillman |first3=Dave |title=The World of Market Pulp |publisher=WOMP, LLC |year=2005 |location=Appleton, Wis |page = 254 |url= |doi= |id= |isbn=0-615-13013-5 }}</ref>

