|colspan="7" align=center|<span style="font-size:95%">
Notes:
*{{dagger}} The storm noted formed or attained Category&nbsp;4 status in the central Pacific basin but may have formed in the eastern Pacific basin
*{{double dagger}} The storm noted attained Category&nbsp;4 status more than once
*<nowiki>*</nowiki> The storm noted was both a Category&nbsp;4 in the eastern and central Pacific basins
*<nowiki>**</nowiki> The storm noted originated in the Atlantic basin, but later intensified into a Category&nbsp;4 hurricane in the eastern Pacific basin
*<nowiki>#</nowiki> Storms that attained Category&nbsp;4 status at one point but intensified into Category&nbsp;5 at a later time are not included.
*As the Pacific hurricane database only goes back to 1949, the [[1943 Mazatlán hurricane]] is not included, although it attained Category&nbsp;4-equivalent winds at 136&nbsp;mph (219&nbsp;km/h). It is unknown if the winds observed were sustained.<ref name="hurdat" /><ref name="mwr-1943">{{cite journal|author=Sumner, Howard C.|author2=Woolard, Edgar W.|author2-link=Edgar W. Woolard|date=November 1943|title=North Atlantic Hurricanes and Tropical Disturbances of 1943|journal=[[Monthly Weather Review]]|format=PDF|volume=71|issue=11|pages=179–183|issn=1520-0493|url=http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/general/lib/lib1/nhclib/mwreviews/1943.pdf|doi=10.1175/1520-0493(1943)71<179:NAHATD>2.0.CO;2|publisher=[[American Meteorological Society]]|bibcode = 1943MWRv...71..179S }}</ref>
</span>
*Storms that formed in the eastern or central Pacific but strengthened to reach Category&nbsp;4 status in the western Pacific basin (west of 180°&nbsp;W) are not included.<ref name="WPac-basin">{{cite web|url=http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/tcfaq/F1.html |title=TCFAQ F1) What regions around the globe have tropical cyclones and who is responsible for forecasting there? |last=Landsea |first=Christopher |work=[[Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory]] |publisher=[[Hurricane Research Division]] |accessdate=2011-12-14 |location=United States |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113000158/http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/tcfaq/F1.html |archivedate=2012-11-13 |df= }}</ref><ref name="Atlantic-HURDAT">{{cite web|url=http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/hurdat/tracks1851to2010_atl_reanal.html|title=HURDAT 1851 – 2010|date=August 2011|work=[[Hurricane Research Division]]|publisher=[[HURDAT]]|accessdate=2011-12-14|location=United States}}</ref>
|}{{clear}}

==Landfalls==
{{bar chart|float=right
| title = [[Landfall (meteorology)|Landfalls]] by month<ref name="hurdat" />
| data_max = 15
| label_type = Month
| data_type = Number of storms
| label1 = June
| data1 = 2
| label2 = August
| data2 = 2
| label3 = September{{#tag:ref|Though [[Hurricane Juliette (2001)|Hurricane Juliette]] of 2001 made a second landfall in October, it did so after it re-generated. The landfall is included in the "September" total but not the "October" total.|group="nb"}}
| data3 = 10
| label4 = October
| data4 = 15
}}
Of the 126&nbsp;Category&nbsp;4 hurricanes that have formed in the eastern and central Pacific basins, 28&nbsp;have made [[landfall (meteorology)|landfall]]. Of them, four made landfall at Category&nbsp;4 intensity, three at Category&nbsp;3, eleven at Categories&nbsp;2 and 1, eight as tropical storms, and six as tropical depressions. Several of these storms weakened slightly after attaining Category&nbsp;4 status as they approached land;<ref name="hurdat"/><ref name="mwr-1943"/> this is usually a result of dry air, shallower water due to [[continental shelf|shelving]], cooler waters, or interaction with land.<ref name="Katrina-TCR">{{cite web|url={{NHC TCR url|id=AL122005_Katrina}}|title=Tropical Cyclone Report&nbsp;— Hurricane Katrina|author1=Knabb, Richard D.|author2=Rhome, Jamie R.|author3=Brown, Daniel P.|date=2011-09-14|publisher=[[National Hurricane Center]]|page=4|accessdate=2011-12-01|location=United States|format=PDF}}</ref> Only in six years&nbsp;– 1976, 1983, 1992, 1997, 2014 and 2018&nbsp;– more than one Category&nbsp;4 hurricane made landfall, and only during one year&nbsp;– 2018 – did four Category&nbsp;4 hurricanes made landfall.<ref name="hurdat"/>
{{clear}}
